description.text:
v1.2, Monday 7 November 2016
This is an advanced prototype of a (full-parametric, customizable) extruder for plastic pellets that can work for common 3D printers, improved from our previous work: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1689212
The parts have to be 3D-printed out of metal (Aluminum and/or stainless steel) by a professional printing service, some can be milled or made with a CNC, and other parts have to be added (stepper motor, couplers, screws, nozzle, fans, flanges, thermistor and heating elements, etc.... Anyway, this prototype can also be printed in plastic (ABS, PLA, PET...) and it may be usable for extruding "soft" pellets (chocolate granules? Play-Doo, wax, ...), without a heating system. We have partially tested it, but more tests and improvements will follow. But will post here the results and any improved version of the design.

From the attached PDF: A unit circle, similar to the one above, is printed on a piece of clear plexiglass. A spindle is affixed at the center of the unit circle. A radius like the one shown below, perhaps printed in red to distinguish it from black lines on a piece of paper, is created on a piece of clear plastic, and is made in such a way that it fits on the spindle, forming a radius that can be turned 360 degrees on the plexiglass unit circle. Individuals can place the plexiglass over any geometry work which involves finding the degrees in an angle, and use it like a protractor to measure any angle in either degrees or radians. Another piece of sheet plastic could be printed with a fully notated protractor in order to make the toolÃ¢ÂÂs measurements more exacting. A Protractor and a unit circle can be combined in this way to make plain the relationship between degrees and radians which is often a source of confusion for students in advanced High School math. Additional radii can also be created and placed over the spindle as well, for use as a learning aid in Trigonometry, when discussing adding and subtracting of radians, or for the special case trigonometric ratios. Overall, the point would be to smooth the transition from the tools and methods of polar to radial geometry.

description.text:
I made a casing to fit a 40mm fan that is placed on the power supply that comes with the Anet A8 printer. Especially in the summer when room temperatures are higher the power supply can get hot. This little fan case reduces the temperature to a safe level.
I designed it in such a way that you can position it anywhere on the outside power supply grid.
I don't recommend placing the fan at the top right corner as this will cause the heat to spread onto the PCB and heat up the components. Instead place the fan in the middle so that the cold air will hit the PCB, flow along the heat sinks and escape through the grid (see picture for guidance).
I'm using a 40mm fan to compliment the size with other parts that I have designed e.g. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1803120 and the fan used on the extruder. Therefore only one type of spare fan is needed.

I hooked up the fan to the 12V output on the power supply.

Please view the pictures for more details.

If you made one please also post a picture of your setup.

Thanks.

Leo

description.text:
This is my first design and it's a very basic "pollen press".
There are three pieces:
1 Cap
1 Chamber
1 Pusher

Assemble by placing the cap on either end of the tube/chamber piece and then load her up with LOTS of pollen. Then use the pusher to condense into a puck. The first time I tried compressing by using both my hands coupled together and squeezed as hard as a could. The results weren't very satisfying as the puck was brittle. I was able to achieve a higher level of success by standing on it with all my weight; however, I do advise to be careful as you might twist your ankle or something standing on it and this is my 'liability exemption'.

ideally a screwing type of top like one of the garlic presses on this site has would be the best, but this definitely does the trick.

NOTE: You will need quite a lot of pollen! I also made the cap radius .2 bigger so I hope it fits better than the one i printed out. The pusher should have a slight bit of space on the sides as if it's too tight the pollen makes it difficult to push it through if it gets trapped on the sides. If you need extra height on the pusher for whatever reason you can use a nickel, it fits quite well.

title: 3Dator Bowden Extruder REMIXED (MK8 GEAR) base mod 1/8"

description.text:
Another simple remix of the 3Dator Bowden Extruder REMIXED (MK8 GEAR) that provides a 1/8" inside thread to take the PC4-01 push fitting for the PTFE tube. I've included the OpenSCAD file that I used to create the mod. With the PC4-M5 push fitting used in this design I noticed unwanted movement of the PTFE tube on retraction as witnessed by 50koruny. The PC4-01 push fitting is supposed to remedy this issue.

The PC4-01 has a BSP thread that is close to M10 in diameter but has a much finer pitch that does not allow an M10 captive nut as a solution. Instead a 1/8" thread has been printed in an extension on the extruder output to capture enough of the push fitting thread to connect properly.

Unfortunately, the STL file generated by OpenSCAD had manyfold issues so I had to repair it. I have used the Microsoft 3D Builder software that comes standard with Windows 10. Cura had no problem slicing the repaired STL.

Update November 16, 2016
Added a mirrored version of the base in case you want to create a mirrored version of the extruder.

Printer:

Velleman Vertex K8400

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

35%

Notes:

Printed in red REAL brand PLA using the 3Dator Bowden Extruder with the 3Dator Bowden Extruder REMIXED (MK8 GEAR) base mod.

The OpenSCAD source depends on the threads library for the english thread module.

There is an option in the OpenSCAD file to create the base in two parts: one of the base proper and another of the extension with the 1/8" thread. This is controlled through the boolean variable whole (default set to true). The idea behind this was to print the thread along the Z-axis to have a sufficiently fine pitch. This extension part must be rotated along the X-axis to make the clips with which it attaches to the base sufficiently strong and flexible. In the end the thread of the base plus extension printed as a whole proved sufficiently accurate. The 1/8" push fitting screwed in just fine.

Update November 16, 2016
The OpenSCAD source has been updated to allow creation of a mirrored version of the base by setting the global parameter mirror_ to true (default set to false).

This is a Customizer-version of the kind of christmas tree as shown by philwild (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:185040). You can set the height, diameter, wall thickness, number of "arms or twigs", twist angle and direction.
Additionally you can add a hole or a small ring to hang the tree up.
And a base circle can be added as well.

Not the easiest print. Adhesion to the bed should be no problem even when using only the small baseplate.
Whithout the foot (like philwild's original), I was not able to print without getting it knocked off. Contact to the bed would only be some 0.5 mm stripes in that case. With the small foot it is 5 mm stripes. With my printer (Makergear M2) the noozle sometimes "makes contact" with on of the "fins" resulting in strange noises but it did not break the print. The really difficult part is the top!
As the tree diameter gets smaller and smaller, the noozle keeps hovering more or less at the exact same spot, transferring a lot of heat down on the print.
At least with PLA, you will definitely need a fan, and set it to 100%. Maybe you even need to additionally blow yourself on the print. Don't faint! It may help to print e.g. four of the trees of same size at once so the noozle moves away letting it cool. I did not try but others have used this technique for other small and high prints..

title: Length, Area, Volume:  Study 1 -- The Cube

description.text:
Design concept by P. Streilein
Riverside High School PLTW Engineering Program
Durham, NC
Modeling by G. Walters Exploring the relationships between length, area, and volume: 1. The Cube This design could be parameterized to generate various unit cubes.
This example is a 6 unit cube (6 cm on a side) which has been separated into 6 equal slices. On each slice is labeled the Length, Width, and Depth (=1 cm). On the top face, the 1cm square units are embossed. On the bottom face are the relationships between length, area, and volume and the area and volume for the slice are calculated. The 6 slices are stacked in the holder which shows the cumulative volume as slices are added. In the case of the 6 unit cube, these are multiples of 36. The student can either start with all of the slices in the holder and work to calculate the total volume of the cube and the remaining volumes as each slice is removed. Or, the student can start with an empty holder and build up to the full cube, calculating layer areas, volumes, and seeing how volume increases as layers are added.

title: ctc replicator dual - z axis lower & upper guide supports

description.text:
After trying in vain to get the Z axis at 90 degrees to the Y in my bot I had to tinker then redesign a set of Z axis guide supports that let me fine tune the angles to get it to 90 degrees from the 88 degrees that my bot seemed to be built at.. That 2 degrees difference seems to be just enough out of true to cause me some strange printing results. Here are 4 different sets of mounts that can be printed that may help somebody set there bot up just a little better if they have a small digital spirit level or another way of finding the correct angle for their bot.

1 x upper rounded corners with normal width cutout mounts.
1 x upper rounded corners with slim width cutout mounts.
1 x upper squared / chamferd corners with normal width cutout mounts.
1 x upper squared / chamferd corners with slim width cutout mounts.
1 x lower rounded corners with normal width cutout mounts.
1 x lower rounded corners with slim width cutout mounts.
1 x lower squared / chamferd corners with normal width cutout mounts.
1 x lower squared / chamferd corners with normal slim cutout mounts.

ns = normal squared/chamferd
nr = normal rounded
ss = slim squared/chamferd
sr = slim rounded

Installation guide

Parts required:-
2 x M3-12mm bolts
6 x M3 16mm bolts
8 x M3 nyloc nuts
8mm drill bit and drill (if you need to drill the holes out to get them on the 8mm guide rods).

Make sure your hbp ( build plate ) is roughly in the center of the bot. Unplugged from both usb and power supply.

  1. remove one side upper guide at a time and remove the guide bar through the hole.
  2. Install 2 nyloc nuts in the hex nut holes (should be a tight fit) then as you slide the guide bar back in thru the top mount hole, slide the upper inner mount onto the bar (you might need to drill the hole out to 8mm depending upon how configured you have your machine for printing exact sizes) so that the nyloc nuts should be facing down towards the bed of the printer. see picture above to get the idea.
  3. continue to slide the guide bar down thru the bearings/bushing of the hbp and into the lower mount.
    4.Put 2 x M3-16mm bolts through the bolt holes in the upper mount and place the upper mount on the guide bar and then press down into the hole. If eveything looks ok slide the internal part up to the top and line up the bolts and tighten them into the nyloc nuts. ( do not over tighten as you need to adjust them at the final stage)

If everything is going good repeat on the other side and you will be halfway done

Lower mounts ( one is easy but the other requires removing the motherboard ) ** humm

Set your bot on its side/back/top (whatever you find easier, I set mine on its left side with the underneath facing me)

  1. easy one first. remove the nuts and bolts from the first lower mount and remove, nice and easy.
  2. install nyloc nuts into the holes on the bottom of the lower mounts.
  3. Set the mount onto the guide bar and push into the hole. now put a washer on an M3-16mm long bolt and from inside the bot insert the bolt through the hole and into the nyloc nut and tighten up a bit.

The hard one..

1 remove the single bolt that keeps the bottom plywood cover in place and remove the cover (put it to one side for fitting back once finished)

  1. Now you need to locate and remove 5 x nyloc nuts and red washers from the bolts that hold the main system board in place.
  2. Once you have the nyloc nuts and washers removed you can lift the main board off the bolts (trying to leave the bolts and white spacers in place) ( you can insert your own swear words here and keep using them untill its back together again)
  3. With the main board loose it should let you gently move it to get access to the final lower mount.
  4. Remove the 2 nuts and bolts holding the lower mount to the case and remove the part.
  5. Fit 2 nyloc nuts into the remaining lower mount and place it onto the guide bar and press it into place, From the inside using the 2 x M3-12mm bolts a 2 washers, insert them into through the case into the guide support and tighten them up a bit (snug not too tight)
  6. the real fun part is getting the main system board back in place without the white spacers going awol. I start by selecting the bolt beside the lcd ribbon cable and line the board up with the bolt and slip it on, once its on slip a red washer on and a nyloc nut and tighten finger tight, select another bolt and repeat the process, once you get all 5 nuts and bolts finger tight you can give the board a whiggle and twiddle and start tightening the nuts down 1/2 turn each nut. once the board seems to be getting tight insert the usb cable from outside through its hole into the socket and move the board untill it all seems to line up by itself, Give the 5 nuts and bolts a gentle tighten up and fingers crossed you are ready to put the bottom plywood cover back on and insert its retaining screw.

The hard part is over unless you need to use the smaller / slimmer version of these mounts and you printed the normal sized version (at least you know how to do it if you need to use the smaller/slimmer ones)

to set these at 90 degrees to the bot you need a small spirit level / digitall angle level.
Make sure the bot is sitting level or as level as you can make it. front right to rear left and front left to rear right, front to back and left to right.
Slacken the upper and lower M3 bolts a few turns so that the whole mount can move and use the small level to find true 90 degrees both left to right and front to back and tighten the bolts up locking the guide rod in place, repeat the process on the other guide rod and make sure the bed goes up and down.

title: Nozzle Extender for Ryobi 40V Cordless Leaf Blower

description.text:
I recently bought a Ryobi 40V cordless leaf blower. I really like it, but the nozzle seems a bit short and I found myself bending over, trying to reach closer to the ground while using it. I noticed that a 2.5" shop-vac extension tube is almost the exact diameter of the output -- if only there was a way to attach them... Not wanting to use duct tape or permanently modify the blower, I designed this mating collar.

Please note that there is a gradual taper from one end to the other. The larger end goes onto the blower, and the smaller end points away from the blower and holds the extension, which is made from:

You'll need one of these from Home Depot: http://www.homedepot.com/p/RIDGID-2-1-2-in-Extension-Wand-Accessory-for-RIDGID-Wet-Dry-Vacs-VT2508/100050604

Cut about 6" starting from the female end and jam that through from the larger end of the collar toward the smaller end. Wedge it in good and tight so it won't come out on its own. You may have to sand down the ridge so it will fit in far enough. Now you can easily install (and remove) the whole assembly onto your blower as needed.

(I'm 5'10" and a 6" extension worked nicely. Adjust as needed.)

I suppose if you have a larger Z axis, you could extend the design and print the whole thing as one piece, or you could design and print a second piece instead of buying the vacuum extension -- but I already had one sitting in my garage and didn't want to spend so much time (and filament) printing it.

Orca V 0.20 ? 0.30 and 0.40 (will not fit v42, has already an geared extruder )

description.text:
Please look below to see the video of this in action!

This is my second generation halloween crow, now with an animated head and blinking eyes. It is in 5 pieces that are designed to be sliced and printed in "vase mode". The crow is about 18" (45cm) long when assembled. The largest section that you will need to print is about 7.25" (19cm) tall and about 5" (13cm) wide. I printed this in black PLA and used hot glue to attach the feet. There is a short section that attaches to the tail so that it can be press-fit to the body. This allows access to the electronics/battery compartment. The controller is an Arduino Uno. The eye holes were created with a drill and the LEDs are press fitted.

The arduino code to run this is attached as CrowServo.ino

I just finished this project today (Oct 31st 2016). I'll be adding more details later.

description.text: I made this iphone mount to hold my phone in either the vertical position while playing music in my car, or in the horizontal position to act as my gps. recently I had been having to make many trips up to 7 hours away and I was using my phone as a gps so often it became dangerous to try to hold it and drive this little gadget is great and works great with the slimmer otter box cases. but it can (could) be used without a case on the phone. description.text:
Here is a case I designed to house the Arduino Mega 2560 + RAMPS controller for my Kossel Delta printer clone. With the included 2020 controller bracket, you can place it anywhere on any of the beams on the Delta printer. The hole layout is for the Arduino Mega 2560.

You will need the following:

2 x M3 T-slot hammer nuts (mount bracket to beam)
2 x M3 6mm screws (mount bracket to beam)
4 x M3 10mm screws. 8mm will work too (mount case to bracket)
2 x M3 20mm screws (mount Arduino Mega 2560 to case)
1 x M3 30mm screw (mount Arduino Mega 2560 to case)

The holes are all 3mm in diameter. You will need to thread the holes first before mounting everything. Custom supports are included that you can break away to expose the end of the controller in the case. The grills are all spaced 2.5mm apart. You can mount pretty much anything to the grills using M3 screws. It will take some effort but they will fit. I intended to mount some fans to the case by screwing them to the grills.
